At the S.E. corner of Thirty-second Avenue, and 78th Streets, showing an old home in the street line owned by W. Locke in 1873 and H. Konken in 1896.

April 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

78th Street, west side, 150 feet south of 32nd Avenue, showing the headquarters of the famous "Black Watch" during the Revolution. It was built more than 200 years ago and during the campaign on Long Island commanding officers of the 42nd Highlanders, it was said, lived in this farmhouse. These views show the original location on Trains Meadow Road, an ancient zigzagging country road, later obliterated. Views 1 and 2 are in a northerly direction; views 3 and 4, in a southerly. In the latter the house is in the center background. See the "New York Herald-Tribune," March 8, 1936.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

78th Street, west side, 150 feet south of 32nd Avenue, showing the headquarters of the famous "Black Watch" during the War for Independence. It was built more than two centuries ago and during the campaign on Long Island commanding officers of the 42nd Highlanders, it was said, lived here. These views show the original location on Trains Meadow Road, an ancient country road, later obliterated. Eugene L. Armbruster refers to the house as the W. Wright farmhouse and also as the Walker farmhouse. See the "New York Herald-Tribune," March 8, 1936.
